@startuml recall-consolidate-tandem
' Component / overview: how the Recall tier snaps onto the Consolidate tier.
' Recall (pgvector) owns lsn > consolidated_lsn; Consolidate (S3 shards +
' sidecars) owns lsn <= consolidated_lsn; the consolidated_lsn watermark is
' the seam. Synchronous writes land in Recall; the index_builder drains
' Recall into a shard and advances the watermark; queries read BOTH tiers
' and merge (recall-wins dedup, L2^2 metric alignment).
'
' NOTE: "Recall <-> Consolidate" here is the WRITE-FRESHNESS axis. It is a
' DIFFERENT axis from the SSD-cache "hot/cold" storage-distance axis in
' ssd-cache-tiers.puml -- do not conflate them. The SSD/RAM cache holds
' disposable copies of consolidated shards and never affects completeness.

title RosalindDB: Recall tier snapped onto the Consolidate tier (RB_RECALL on)

skinparam componentStyle rectangle
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam defaultFontName Helvetica
skinparam defaultFontSize 12
skinparam ArrowFontSize 11
skinparam NoteFontSize 10
skinparam wrapWidth 220

actor "client" as client

component "cp\n(Control Plane,\npublic origin)" as cp
component "query_dp\n(union + merge)" as dp
component "index_builder\n(consolidate = compaction,\nsingle replica, advisory-locked)" as builder
queue "CONSOLIDATE topic\n(best-effort enqueue:\ncap exceeded / idle sweep)" as q

package "Write-freshness axis (this design)" {
  database "Recall tier\npgvector (data-plane,\nRB_RECALL_DSN)\nrows: (tenant, dataset, id,\nembedding, metadata, lsn, deleted)\nOWNS lsn > consolidated_lsn" as recall
  database "shard_catalog\n(control-plane PG)\nrow per shard + consolidated_lsn\n= the WATERMARK / seam" as catalog
  cloud "Consolidate tier\nobject store: FAISS shards\n+ sidecars\nOWNS lsn <= consolidated_lsn" as os
}

' ---- Synchronous write path: -> Recall ----
client -down-> cp : (1) POST /vectors (sync)
cp -down-> recall : (2) nextval(lsn_seq);\nUPSERT (.. , lsn, deleted)\n[durable -> queryable now]
cp -right-> q : (3) enqueue CONSOLIDATE\n(after durable write)
cp --> client : 200 OK {accepted, rejected, errors}

' ---- Consolidation: drains Recall -> shard, advances watermark ----
q -down-> builder : signal
builder -up-> recall : (A) snapshot lsn <= N\n(live rows + tombstones)
builder -down-> os : (B) build + write shard + sidecar\n(apply tombstones via _remove_ids)
builder -right-> catalog : (C) COMMIT consolidated_lsn = N\n[I2: commit BEFORE trim]
builder -up-> recall : (D) grace-bounded TRIM\nlsn <= 2nd-newest shard's watermark\n[I2 after commit, I4 grace, idempotent]

' ---- Query: reads BOTH tiers, merges ----
client -down-> cp : (Q1) POST /query
cp -down-> dp
dp -right-> catalog : (Q2) resolve latest shard S +\nits consolidated_lsn(S)  [I3 pairing]
dp -down-> os : (Q3) FAISS search S (via SSD/RAM cache)\n-> cold hits in L2^2
dp -up-> recall : (Q4) exact brute-force\nWHERE NOT deleted, lsn > consolidated_lsn(S)
dp -> dp : (Q5) merge: square pgvector L2 -> L2^2,\nrecall-wins dedup, drop tombstoned ids,\nsort asc, take top_k
dp --> client : {matches, mode, ...}

note bottom of catalog
  consolidated_lsn is the single number that
  partitions every vector (I1):
    lsn <= W  -> Consolidate (shard)
    lsn >  W  -> Recall (pgvector)
  Each vector has exactly one lsn, so it is in
  exactly one tier. Union = complete.
end note

note right of recall
  Brute-force exact (no ANN) over a SMALL set:
  consolidation cadence -- not data size -- bounds
  it (cap RB_RECALL_MAX_ROWS, idle drain to 0).
  The per-write path never touches control-plane PG.
end note

note bottom of os
  Immutable, versioned shards (the Consolidate
  tier). The SSD/RAM cache in front of this is a
  SEPARATE storage-distance axis; a cache miss is
  only slower, never incomplete.
end note

@enduml
